'''Yves Rousseau''' is a French inventor and aviator credited with multiple ultralight aircraft [[Fédération Aéronautique Internationale|FAI]] world records. He has received international recognition for his 13 years of work on human-powered [[ornithopter]] flight. Rousseau attempted his first human-powered flight with flapping wings in 1995.
In 2005, Rousseau was given the [[Paul Tissandier Diploma]], awarded to those who have served the cause of aviation in general and sporting aviation in particular, by their work, initiative, devotion or in other ways. After having made oscillate the wings of a [[hang glider]], Yves mounted his patented flapping mechanism on a 'Vector' ultralight airplane and on 20 April 2006, at his 212th attempt, he succeeded in flying a distance of 64 metres, observed by officials of the Aero Club de France. Unfortunately, on his 213th flight attempt, a gust of wind led to a wing breaking up, causing the pilot to be gravely injured and rendered [[paraplegic]].<ref>[http://www.fai.org/awards/recipient.asp?id=4181 FAI award] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070707182622/http://www.fai.org/awards/recipient.asp?id=4181 |date=7 July 2007 }}</ref>
Rousseau patented a few ultralight aircraft, including the wheeled prone ultralights '''Pulcim 220''', the '''Pulcim 521''' and a foot-launched [[powered hang glider]] harness called '''Relax 220'''.<ref>[https://archive.is/20090819151614/http://perso.orange.fr/pulma1/Un%20peu%20d'histoire.htm Yves Rousseau marketed aircraft]</ref>
